'''BlackRock, Inc.''' is an American [[Multinational corporation|multinational]] [[investment company]]. Founded in 1988, initially as an [[enterprise risk management]] and [[fixed income]] institutional [[asset manager]], BlackRock is the world's largest asset manager, with US$11.5{{nbsp}}trillion in [[assets under management]] {{as of|2023|12|31|lc=y|df=US}}.<ref name=10K /> [[Headquartered]] in [[New York City]], BlackRock has 70 offices in 30 countries, and clients in 100 countries.

BlackRock is the manager of the [[iShares]] group of [[exchange-traded fund]]s, and along with [[The Vanguard Group]] and [[State Street Corporation|State Street]], it is considered to be one of the Big Three [[index fund]] managers.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Bebchuk |first1=Lucian |author-link=Lucian Bebchuk |last2=Hirst |first2=Scott |date=December 2019 |title=Index Funds and the Future of Corporate Governance: Theory, Evidence, and Policy |url=https://columbialawreview.org/content/index-funds-and-the-future-of-corporate-governance-theory-evidence-and-policy/ |journal=[[Columbia Law Review]] |volume=119 |issue=8 |pages=2029–2146 |ssrn=3282794 |access-date=9 December 2022 |archive-date=29 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221129143321/https://columbialawreview.org/content/index-funds-and-the-future-of-corporate-governance-theory-evidence-and-policy/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=McLaughlin |first1=David |last2=Massa |first2=Annie |date=9 January 2020 |title=The Hidden Dangers of the Great Index Fund Takeover |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2020-01-09/the-hidden-dangers-of-the-great-index-fund-takeover |access-date=7 June 2021 |website=Bloomberg Businessweek |archive-date=7 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210607183943/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2020-01-09/the-hidden-dangers-of-the-great-index-fund-takeover |url-status=live }}</ref> Its [[Aladdin (BlackRock)|Aladdin]] software keeps track of investment portfolios for many major financial institutions and its BlackRock Solutions division provides financial [[risk management]] services. As of 2023, BlackRock was ranked 229th on the [[Fortune 500|''Fortune'' 500]] list of the largest United States corporations by revenue.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://fortune.com/company/blackrock/fortune500/ |title=BlackRock |date=5 June 2023 |access-date=2024-01-18 |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231215221803/https://fortune.com/company/blackrock/fortune500/ |archive-date=2023-12-15 |url-status=live}}</ref> 

BlackRock has sought to position itself as an industry leader in [[environmental, social, and governance]] (ESG) considerations in investments.<ref name="g939">{{cite web | last=Binnie | first=Isla | title=BlackRock's Fink says he's stopped using 'weaponised' term ESG | website=Reuters | date=26 June 2023 | url=https://www.reuters.com/business/environment/blackrocks-fink-says-hes-stopped-using-weaponised-term-esg-2023-06-26/ | access-date=19 July 2024}}</ref> The U.S. states of West Virginia,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-01-18 |title=West Virginia Treasury Drops BlackRock Over Stance on Climate Risk |url=https://www.institutionalinvestor.com/article/2bstlkf8328cq1951648w/corner-office/west-virginia-treasury-drops-blackrock-over-stance-on-climate-risk |access-date=2024-11-26 |website=Institutional Investor |language=en}}</ref> Florida,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Downey |first=Renzo |date=2022-12-01 |title=Florida divests $2B from BlackRock as movement against woke investing matures |url=https://floridapolitics.com/archives/573678-florida-divests-2b-from-blackrock-as-movement-against-woke-investing-matures/ |access-date=2024-11-26 |website=Florida Politics - Campaigns & Elections. Lobbying & Government. |language=en-US}}</ref> and Louisiana<ref>{{Cite web |last=Muller |first=Wesley |date=2022-10-06 |title=Treasurer pulls Louisiana investments out of BlackRock • Louisiana Illuminator |url=https://lailluminator.com/2022/10/05/treasurer-pulls-louisiana-investments-out-of-blackrock/ |access-date=2024-11-26 |website=Louisiana Illuminator |language=en-US}}</ref> have divested money away from or refuse to do business with the firm because of its ESG policies. BlackRock has been criticized for investing in companies that are involved in [[fossil fuels]] and the [[arms industry]].   BlackRock has also received other criticism for investing in the [[People's Liberation Army]] and getting involved in [[Human rights in China|the conflict between the Chinese government and theocratic rights claimants]]. The company has also faced criticism for its close ties with the [[Federal Reserve]] during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].

==History==
===1988–1999===
BlackRock was founded in 1988 by [[Larry Fink]], [[Robert S. Kapito]], [[Susan Wagner]], Barbara Novick, Ben Golub, Hugh Frater, Ralph Schlosstein, and Keith Anderson<ref>{{Cite web |last=Appell |first=Douglas |date=9 July 2012 |title=BlackRock departures spur talk about Fink's future |url=https://www.pionline.com/article/20120709/PRINT/307099977/blackrock-departures-spur-talk-about-finks-future |access-date=15 April 2019 |website=Pensions & Investments |language=en |archive-date=15 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415175234/https://www.pionline.com/article/20120709/PRINT/307099977/blackrock-departures-spur-talk-about-finks-future |url-status=live }}</ref> to provide institutional clients with asset management services from a risk management perspective.<ref>{{Cite news |date=5 December 2013 |title=The rise of BlackRock |newspaper=The Economist |url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/2013/12/05/the-rise-of-blackrock |access-date=15 April 2019 |issn=0013-0613 |archive-date=4 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220504013557/https://www.economist.com/leaders/2013/12/05/the-rise-of-blackrock |url-status=live }}</ref> Fink, Kapito, Golub and Novick had worked together at [[First Boston]], where Fink and his team were pioneers in the [[Mortgage-backed security|mortgage-backed securities]] market in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Larry Fink Q&A: "I Don't Identify as Powerful" |newspaper=Bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2017-blackrock-larry-fink-interview/ |access-date=15 April 2019 |archive-date=30 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220430024242/https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2017-blackrock-larry-fink-interview/ |url-status=live }}</ref> During Fink's tenure, he had lost $90&nbsp;million as head of First Boston. That experience was the motivation to develop what he and the others considered to be excellent risk management and fiduciary practices. Initially, Fink sought funding (for initial operating capital) from [[Peter G. Peterson|Peter Peterson]] of [[The Blackstone Group]] who believed in Fink's vision of a firm devoted to risk management. Peterson called it Blackstone Financial Management.<ref name=":4">{{Cite book |last1=Carey |first1=David |last2=Morris |first2=John E. |date=2012 |title=King of Capital: The Remarkable Rise, Fall, and Rise Again of Steve Schwarzman and Blackstone |publisher=Crown Publishing Group |isbn=978-0307886026 |page=59 |language=en |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DE8jTajp7PAC&pg=PA59 |access-date=11 April 2019 |archive-date=24 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240224164531/https://books.google.com/books?id=DE8jTajp7PAC&pg=PA59#v=onepage&q&f=false |url-status=live }}</ref> In exchange for a 50% stake in the bond business, Blackstone initially gave Fink and his team a $5&nbsp;million credit line. Within months, the business had turned profitable, and by 1989 the group's assets had quadrupled to $2.7&nbsp;billion. The percent of the stake owned by Blackstone also fell to 40%, compared to Fink's staff.<ref name=":4" />

By 1992, Blackstone had a stake equating to about 36% of the company, and [[Stephen A. Schwarzman]] and Fink were considering selling shares to the public.<ref name=heroic/> The firm adopted the name BlackRock, and was managing $17&nbsp;billion in assets by the end of the year. At the end of 1994, BlackRock was managing $53&nbsp;billion.<ref name="main-history">{{Cite web |title=History |url=https://www.blackrock.com/corporate/about-us/blackrock-history |publisher=BlackRock |access-date=7 April 2023 |archive-date=16 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516014614/https://www.blackrock.com/corporate/about-us/blackrock-history |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1994, Schwarzman and Fink had an internal dispute over methods of compensation and equity.<ref name=heroic/> Fink wanted to share equity with new hires, to lure talent from banks, unlike Schwarzman, who did not want to further lower Blackstone's stake.<ref name=heroic/> They agreed to part ways, and Schwarzman sold BlackRock, a decision he later called a "heroic mistake."<ref name=heroic>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-09-30/schwarzman-says-selling-blackrock-was-heroic-mistake | title=Schwarzman Says Selling BlackRock Was 'Heroic' Mistake | first=Devin | last=Banerjee | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=30 September 2013 | url-access=limited | access-date=5 March 2017 | archive-date=16 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211216022421/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-09-30/schwarzman-says-selling-blackrock-was-heroic-mistake | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=BlackRock is Wall Street's object of fantasy M&A | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-blackrock-blackstone-group-breakingvi/breakingviews-blackrock-is-wall-streets-object-of-fantasy-ma-idUSKBN1YR1JI | last1=Foley | first1=John | last2=Cox | first2=Rob | work=[[Reuters]] | date=23 December 2019 | access-date=26 October 2021 | archive-date=1 May 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501160704/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-blackrock-blackstone-group-breakingvi/breakingviews-blackrock-is-wall-streets-object-of-fantasy-ma-idUSKBN1YR1JI | url-status=live }}</ref> In June 1994, Blackstone sold a mortgage-securities unit with $23&nbsp;billion in assets to [[PNC Financial Services]] for $240&nbsp;million.<ref name="fortune-admired" /> The unit had traded mortgages and other fixed-income assets, and during the sales process the unit changed its name from Blackstone Financial Management to BlackRock Financial Management.<ref name=heroic/> Schwarzman remained with Blackstone, while Fink became chairman and CEO of BlackRock.<ref name=heroic/>

=== 1999–2009 ===
On October 1, 1999, BlackRock became a public company, selling shares at $14 each via an [[initial public offering]] on the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref name=main-history/><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://money.cnn.com/1999/09/26/markets/ipos/ | title=Here come the IPOs |publisher=[[CNN]] | date=26 September 1999 | access-date=7 April 2023 | archive-date=8 April 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230408061452/https://money.cnn.com/1999/09/26/markets/ipos/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Agnew |first=Harriet |date=10 October 2021 |title=BlackRock: 'the journey of a single man' |url=https://www.ft.com/content/62f577cc-39c2-4631-83f0-f5ad95c41f2d |work=[[Financial Times]] |access-date=19 January 2024 |archive-date=19 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240119213952/https://www.ft.com/content/62f577cc-39c2-4631-83f0-f5ad95c41f2d |url-status=live }}</ref> By the end of 1999, BlackRock was managing $165&nbsp;billion in assets.<ref name=main-history/> BlackRock grew both organically and by acquisition. In 2000, under the direction of [[Charles Hallac]], BlackRock launched BlackRock Solutions, its analytics and risk management division. The division grew from the [[Aladdin (BlackRock)|Aladdin System]], the enterprise investment system, Green Package, the Risk Reporting Service, PAG (portfolio analytics), and AnSer, the interactive analytics.<ref name="economist.com">[https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21591164-getting-15-trillion-assets-single-risk-management-system-huge-achievement "Briefing: BlackRock – The Monolith and the Markets"] ({{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826094406/http://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21591164-getting-15-trillion-assets-single-risk-management-system-huge-achievement |date=26 August 2018 }}), ''[[The Economist]]'', 7 December 2013, pp. 24–26.</ref> 

In August 2004, BlackRock made its first major acquisition, buying State Street Research & Management's holding company SSRM Holdings, Inc. from [[MetLife]] for $325&nbsp;million in cash and $50&nbsp;million in stock. The acquisition increased BlackRock's assets under management from $314&nbsp;billion to $325&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=BlackRock Acquiring State Street Research from MetLife |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20040826005225/en/BlackRock-Purchase-SSRM-Holdings-MetLife-BlackRock-Hold |publisher=[[Business Wire]] |date=24 August 2004 |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=29 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210129230140/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20040826005225/en/BlackRock-Purchase-SSRM-Holdings-MetLife-BlackRock-Hold |url-status=live }}</ref> The deal included the mutual-fund business State Street Research & Management in 2005.<ref name=fortune-admired/>

BlackRock merged with [[Merrill Lynch & Co.|Merrill Lynch]]'s Investment Managers division (MLIM) in 2006,<ref name=main-history/><ref>{{Cite news |title=BlackRock and a hard place |url=https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2006/02/16/blackrock-and-a-hard-place |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |date=16 February 2006 |access-date=7 April 2023 |archive-date=7 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230407051632/https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2006/02/16/blackrock-and-a-hard-place |url-status=live }}</ref> halving PNC's ownership and giving Merrill a 49.5% stake in the company.<ref>{{Cite web |title=BlackRock, Merrill fund unit complete merger |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/merrill-lynch-investment-managers-blackrock-close-merger |last=Spence |first=John |website=[[MarketWatch]] |date=2 October 2006 |url-access=limited |access-date=11 April 2019 |archive-date=1 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501165036/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/merrill-lynch-investment-managers-blackrock-close-merger |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2007, BlackRock acquired the fund-of-funds business of Quellos Capital Management.<ref name="quellos">{{Cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2007/06/26/blackrock-to-buy-quellos-fund-of-funds-business.html | title=BlackRock to Buy Quellos Fund of Funds Business | agency=[[Reuters]] |publisher=[[CNBC]] | date=26 June 2007 | access-date=7 April 2023 | archive-date=7 April 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230407040918/https://www.cnbc.com/id/19430953 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=DeSilver |first=Drew |title=Quellos is selling unit to BlackRock in $1.72 billion deal |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/quellos-is-selling-unit-to-blackrock-in-172-billion-deal/ |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=27 June 2007 |access-date=10 March 2020 |archive-date=15 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210615161712/https://www.seattletimes.com/business/quellos-is-selling-unit-to-blackrock-in-172-billion-deal/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In April 2009, BlackRock acquired R3 Capital Management, LLC and management of its $1.5&nbsp;billion fund.<ref>{{Cite news |title=BlackRock to Acquire R3 Capital |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2009/04/17/blackrock-to-acquire-r3-capital/ |date=17 April 2009 |access-date=9 May 2017 |archive-date=2 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220502081859/https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2009/04/17/blackrock-to-acquire-r3-capital/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2009, BlackRock Solutions was retained by the [[U.S. Treasury Department]]<ref name="bb-power">{{Cite web |last=Kolhatkar |first=Sheelah |title=Fink Builds BlackRock Powerhouse Without Goldman Sachs Backlash |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-09/larry-fink-builds-blackrock-into-powerhouse-without-goldman-sachs-backlash.html |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=9 December 2010 |access-date=5 March 2017 |archive-date=22 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022005135/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-09/larry-fink-builds-blackrock-into-powerhouse-without-goldman-sachs-backlash.html |url-status=live }}</ref> to analyze, unwind, and price the [[toxic asset]]s that were owned by [[Bear Stearns]], [[American International Group]], [[Freddie Mac]], [[Morgan Stanley]], and other financial firms that were affected in the [[2007–2008 financial crisis]].<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Rappaport |first1=Liz |last2=Craig |first2=Susanne |title=BlackRock Wears Multiple Hats |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124269131342732625 |date=19 May 2009 |issn=0099-9660 |access-date=24 January 2019 |archive-date=1 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501163758/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124269131342732625 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="vfair-job">Andrews, Suzanna. [http://www.vanityfair.com/business/features/2010/04/fink-201004 Larry Fink's $12 Trillion Shadow] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228143648/http://www.vanityfair.com/business/features/2010/04/fink-201004 |date=28 February 2011 }}, ''Vanity Fair'', April 2010: "There is little doubt among the financial establishment in Washington and on Wall Street that BlackRock was the best choice to handle the government's problems."</ref> The [[Federal Reserve]] allowed BlackRock to superintend the $130&nbsp;billion-debt settlement of [[Bear Stearns]] and [[American International Group]].<ref name="Wash_Post" />
===2010–2019===
In February 2010, to raise capital needed during the financial crisis, [[Barclays]] sold its Barclays Global Investors (BGI) unit, which included its exchange traded fund business, [[iShares]], to BlackRock for US$13.5&nbsp;billion and Barclays acquired a near-20% stake in BlackRock.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.investmentnews.com/blackrock-wraps-up-merger-with-barclays-global-investors-25639 | title=BlackRock wraps up merger with Barclays Global Investors | agency=[[Associated Press]] | date=16 February 2010 | access-date=7 April 2023 | archive-date=7 April 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230407040919/https://www.investmentnews.com/blackrock-wraps-up-merger-with-barclays-global-investors-25639 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=US giant BlackRock buys arm of Barclays bank |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/jun/12/blackrock-to-buy-barclays-bank-arm |date=12 June 2009 |access-date=8 May 2017 |archive-date=1 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501160704/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/jun/12/blackrock-to-buy-barclays-bank-arm |url-status=live }}</ref> On April 1, 2011, BlackRock was added as a component of the [[S&P 500]] [[stock market index]].<ref name="bweek-replace">{{Cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/blackrock-sp500/update-1-blackrock-to-join-sp-500-index-idUSN2929979120110329 | title=BlackRock to join S&P 500 index | work=[[Reuters]] | date=29 March 2011 | access-date=7 April 2023 | archive-date=7 April 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230407051632/https://www.reuters.com/article/blackrock-sp500/update-1-blackrock-to-join-sp-500-index-idUSN2929979120110329 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=http://archive.boston.com/business/healthcare/articles/2011/03/29/blackrock_to_join_sp_500_index_replacing_genzyme/ | title=BlackRock to join S&P 500 index, replacing Genzyme | work=[[The Boston Globe]] | date=29 March 2011 | access-date=7 April 2023 | archive-date=7 April 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230407051632/http://archive.boston.com/business/healthcare/articles/2011/03/29/blackrock_to_join_sp_500_index_replacing_genzyme/ | url-status=live }}</ref> In 2013, ''Fortune'' listed BlackRock on its annual list of the world's 50 Most Admired Companies.<ref name="fortune-admired">{{Cite news |title=BlackRock: The $4.3 trillion force |work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |url=https://fortune.com/2014/07/07/blackrock-larry-fink/ |first=Carol J. |last=Loomis |date=7 July 2014 |access-date=7 April 2023 |archive-date=4 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704190341/https://fortune.com/2014/07/07/blackrock-larry-fink/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2014,<ref name="fortune-admired" /> BlackRock's $4&nbsp;trillion under management made it the "world's biggest asset manager".<ref name="econ-br">{{Cite news |title=Shadow and substance |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |url=https://www.economist.com/news/special-report/21601621-banks-retreat-wake-financial-crisis-shadow-banks-are-taking-growing |date=10 May 2014 |access-date=24 August 2017 |archive-date=1 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201192843/https://www.economist.com/news/special-report/21601621-banks-retreat-wake-financial-crisis-shadow-banks-are-taking-growing |url-status=live }}</ref> At the end of 2014, the [[Sovereign Wealth Fund Institute]] reported that 65% of Blackrock's assets under management were made up of [[institutional investor]]s.<ref name="swf-institute">{{Cite web |date=n.d. |title=Is BlackRock Too Big |url=https://www.swfinstitute.org/news/26040/is-blackrock-too-big |access-date=9 February 2015 |website=Sovereign Wealth Fund Institute |archive-date=29 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210129230152/https://www.swfinstitute.org/news/26040/is-blackrock-too-big |url-status=live }}</ref>

By June 30, 2015, BlackRock had US$4.721&nbsp;trillion of assets under management.<ref>{{Cite news |date=14 July 2016 |title=BlackRock profit falls as shift from stocks hits fee revenue |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-blackrock-results-idUSKCN0ZU13V |access-date=15 January 2019 |archive-date=8 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201108144027/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-blackrock-results-idUSKCN0ZU13V |url-status=live }}</ref> On August 26, 2015, BlackRock entered into a definitive agreement to acquire [[FutureAdvisor]],<ref name="future-advisor">{{Cite press release |title=BlackRock to Acquire FutureAdvisor |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20150826005586/en/BlackRock-to-Acquire-FutureAdvisor |access-date=26 August 2015 |website=Business Wire |date=26 August 2015 |publisher=BlackRock |archive-date=24 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230624051856/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20150826005586/en/BlackRock-to-Acquire-FutureAdvisor |url-status=live }}</ref> a digital wealth management provider with reported assets under management of $600&nbsp;million.<ref name="future-tech">{{Cite web |last=Tepper |first=Fitz |date=24 June 2015 |title=YC Alum FutureAdvisor Is Now Managing $600 Million In Assets |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/24/yc-alum-futureadvisor-is-now-managing-600-million/ |access-date=12 September 2015 |publisher=TechCrunch |archive-date=1 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501054456/https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/24/yc-alum-futureadvisor-is-now-managing-600-million/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Under the deal, FutureAdvisor would operate as a business within BlackRock Solutions (BRS).<ref name=future-advisor/> BlackRock announced in November 2015 that they would wind down the BlackRock Global Ascent hedge fund after losses. The Global Ascent fund had been its only dedicated global macro fund, as BlackRock was "better known for its mutual funds and exchange traded funds." At the time, BlackRock managed $51&nbsp;billion in hedge funds, with $20&nbsp;billion of that in funds of hedge funds.<ref name="fund-losses">{{Cite news |last=Stevenson |first=Alexandra |date=18 November 2015 |title=BlackRock to Wind Down Macro Hedge Fund |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/19/business/dealbook/blackrock-to-wind-down-macro-hedge-fund.html |access-date=19 November 2015 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=3 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220503212718/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/19/business/dealbook/blackrock-to-wind-down-macro-hedge-fund.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In March 2017, BlackRock, after a six-month review led by [[Mark Wiseman]], initiated a restructuring of its $8 billion actively-managed fund business, resulting in the departure of seven portfolio managers and a $25 million charge in the second quarter, replacing certain funds with quantitative investment strategies.<ref name="ft-cuts">{{Cite news |date=27 March 2017 |title=BlackRock cuts ranks of stockpicking fund managers |work=[[Financial Times]] |url=https://www.ft.com/content/b0056320-13e3-11e7-b0c1-37e417ee6c76 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329232211/https://www.ft.com/content/b0056320-13e3-11e7-b0c1-37e417ee6c76 |archive-date=29 March 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |access-date=30 March 2017 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> By April 2017, [[iShares]] business accounted for $1.41 trillion, or 26%, of BlackRock's total assets under management, and 37% of BlackRock's base fee income.<ref name="ft-record">{{Cite news |last=Foley |first=Stephen |date=19 April 2017 |title=BlackRock assets under management hit $5.4tn on record ETF inflows |work=[[Financial Times]] |url=https://www.ft.com/content/adeae206-2502-11e7-8691-d5f7e0cd0a16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170430062420/https://www.ft.com/content/adeae206-2502-11e7-8691-d5f7e0cd0a16 |archive-date=30 April 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |access-date=10 May 2017 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Also in April 2017, BlackRock backed the inclusion of mainland Chinese shares in MSCI's global index for the first time.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hughes |first=Jennifer |title=BlackRock backs mainland China shares for MSCI benchmarks |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=20 April 2017 |url=https://www.ft.com/content/6f0943e6-257c-11e7-8691-d5f7e0cd0a16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423060903/https://www.ft.com/content/6f0943e6-257c-11e7-8691-d5f7e0cd0a16 |archive-date=23 April 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |url-access=subscription |access-date=10 May 2017 }}</ref>

===2020–present===
In January 2020, [[PNC Financial Services]] sold its stake in BlackRock for $14.4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sabatini |first=Patricia |title=PNC sold its shares to Blackrock stake for $14.4 billion |work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |url=https://www.post-gazette.com/business/pittsburgh-company-news/2020/05/15/PNC-sells-Blackrock-stake-for-14-4-billion/stories/202005150123 |date=15 May 2020 |access-date=4 March 2021 |archive-date=30 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730065935/https://www.post-gazette.com/business/pittsburgh-company-news/2020/05/15/PNC-sells-Blackrock-stake-for-14-4-billion/stories/202005150123 |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2020, the [[Federal Reserve]] chose BlackRock to manage two corporate bond-buying programs in response to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref name="Wash_Post" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" /> This also included the $500&nbsp;billion Primary Market Corporate Credit Facility (PMCCF) and the Secondary Market Corporate Credit Facility (SMCCF), as well as purchase by the [[Federal Reserve]] of commercial mortgage-backed securities (CMBS) guaranteed by [[Government National Mortgage Association]], [[Fannie Mae]], or [[Freddie Mac]].<ref name="Wash_Post">Annie Massa. [https://web.archive.org/web/20200618233642/https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/why-blackrock-has-a-role-in-the-fed-bond-buying-spree/2020/05/21/853f461c-9b74-11ea-ad79-eef7cd734641_story.html?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=wp_business Why BlackRock Has a Role in the Fed Bond-Buying Spree], ''The Washington Post'', 22 May 2020</ref><ref name=":1">Sophie Baker. [https://www.pionline.com/markets/fed-chooses-blackrock-pandemic-support-programs Fed chooses BlackRock for pandemic support programs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210123015149/https://www.pionline.com/markets/fed-chooses-blackrock-pandemic-support-programs |date=23 January 2021 }}, ''Pensions & Investments'', 25 March 2020</ref><ref name=":2">Jonnelle Marte. [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-fed-primarycredit/fed-opens-primary-market-corporate-bond-facility-idUSKBN2402J6 Fed opens primary market corporate bond facility] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210131052032/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-fed-primarycredit/fed-opens-primary-market-corporate-bond-facility-idUSKBN2402J6 |date=31 January 2021 }}, ''Reuters'', 29 June 2020</ref> In August 2020, BlackRock received approval from the [[China Securities Regulatory Commission]] to set up a mutual fund business in the country. This made BlackRock the first global asset manager to get consent from the Chinese government to start operations in the country.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Zacks Equity Research |title=BlackRock Gets Nod to Set Up Mutual Fund Business in China (Revised) |url=https://www.nasdaq.com/articles/blackrock-gets-nod-to-set-up-mutual-fund-business-in-china-revised-2020-09-02 |work=[[Nasdaq]] |date=2 September 2020 |access-date=16 September 2020 |archive-date=1 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501160707/https://www.nasdaq.com/articles/blackrock-gets-nod-to-set-up-mutual-fund-business-in-china-revised-2020-09-02 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=BlackRock Gets Nod to Set Up Mutual Fund Business in China (Revised) |url=https://news.yahoo.com/blackrock-gets-nod-set-mutual-135001227.html |access-date=16 September 2020 |website=news.yahoo.com |date=7 September 2020 |language=en-US |archive-date=7 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210907123428/https://news.yahoo.com/blackrock-gets-nod-set-mutual-135001227.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In November 2021, Blackrock lowered its investment in India while increasing investment in China. The firm maintains a dedicated India Fund, through which it invests in Indian start-ups [[Byju's]], [[Paytm]], and [[Pine Labs]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 November 2021 |title=World's biggest asset manager BlackRock trimming investments in India, more optimistic on China |url=https://theprint.in/economy/worlds-biggest-asset-manager-blackrock-trimming-investments-in-india-more-optimistic-on-china/770519/ |access-date=24 March 2022 |website=ThePrint |language=en-US |archive-date=1 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501160707/https://theprint.in/economy/worlds-biggest-asset-manager-blackrock-trimming-investments-in-india-more-optimistic-on-china/770519/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=BlackRock says it's time to buy China stocks and trim India exposure: Report |url=https://www.businesstoday.in/markets/stocks/story/blackrock-says-its-time-to-buy-china-stocks-and-trim-india-exposure-report-313143-2021-11-23 |access-date=24 March 2022 |website=Business Today |date=23 November 2021 |language=en |archive-date=24 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220324115949/https://www.businesstoday.in/markets/stocks/story/blackrock-says-its-time-to-buy-china-stocks-and-trim-india-exposure-report-313143-2021-11-23 |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 28, 2022, it was announced that BlackRock and [[Volodymyr Zelensky]] had coordinated a role for the company in the reconstruction of Ukraine.<ref name=":7">{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Elliot |date=28 December 2022 |title=Zelenskyy, BlackRock CEO Fink agree to coordinate Ukraine investment |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/12/28/zelenskyy-blackrock-ceo-fink-agree-to-coordinate-ukraine-investment.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221230100238/https://www.cnbc.com/2022/12/28/zelenskyy-blackrock-ceo-fink-agree-to-coordinate-ukraine-investment.html |archive-date=30 December 2022 |work=[[CNBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Schonfeld |first=Zach |date=28 December 2022 |title=Zelensky agrees to Ukraine rebuild investment with BlackRock CEO |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/3790699-zelensky-agrees-to-ukraine-rebuild-investment-with-blackrock-ceo/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221229172625/https://thehill.com/policy/international/3790699-zelensky-agrees-to-ukraine-rebuild-investment-with-blackrock-ceo/ |archive-date=29 December 2022 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]}}</ref> This was after BlackRock CEO Larry Fink and Zelensky met over a video conference in September, 2022.<ref name=":7" /> In April 2023, the company was hired to sell $114&nbsp;billion in assets of [[Signature Bank]] and [[Silicon Valley Bank]] after the [[2023 United States banking crisis]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-04-05/blackrock-hired-to-sell-114-billion-in-failed-banks-securities | title=BlackRock to Sell $114 Billion of Failed Banks' Securities | first1=Dan | last1=Reichl | first2=Silla | last2=Brush | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=5 April 2023 | url-access=limited | access-date=7 April 2023 | archive-date=8 April 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230408142949/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-04-05/blackrock-hired-to-sell-114-billion-in-failed-banks-securities | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.ft.com/content/0db00ba2-6603-4d09-b736-60a0307bc75b | title=BlackRock to manage $114bn of asset disposals after US bank failures | first1=Jennifer | last1=Hughes | first2=Brooke | last2=Masters | work=[[Financial Times]] | date=5 April 2023 | access-date=7 April 2023 | archive-date=7 April 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230407040918/https://www.ft.com/content/0db00ba2-6603-4d09-b736-60a0307bc75b | url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2023, BlackRock filed an application with the United States [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) to launch a Spot [[Bitcoin]] [[Exchange-Traded Fund]] (ETF), and in November 2023 it filed another application for a Spot [[Ethereum]] ETF. The spot bitcoin ETF filing and 10 others were approved on January 10, 2024.<ref>{{cite news |last=Yue |first=Frances |title=BlackRock is applying for a spot bitcoin ETF. Here's why it matters to the crypto industry. |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/why-blackrock-is-reportedly-close-to-applying-for-bitcoin-etf-despite-regulatory-pressure-on-crypto-38aa1df9 |access-date=6 December 2023 |work=Market Watch |archive-date=7 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231207180251/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/why-blackrock-is-reportedly-close-to-applying-for-bitcoin-etf-despite-regulatory-pressure-on-crypto-38aa1df9 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kostas |first=Leo |title=How Investors Can Leverage The Introduction Of Crypto ETFs |url=https://www.benzinga.com/markets/cryptocurrency/23/11/36031837/how-investors-can-leverage-the-introduction-of-crypto-etfs |access-date=6 December 2023 |work=Benzinga |archive-date=5 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231205173814/https://www.benzinga.com/markets/cryptocurrency/23/11/36031837/how-investors-can-leverage-the-introduction-of-crypto-etfs |url-status=live }}</ref> On January 19, 2024, the iShares Bitcoin Trust ETF (IBIT) was the first spot bitcoin ETF to reach $1&nbsp;billion in volume.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brewster |first=Lucy |date=19 January 2024 |title=Spot Bitcoin ETF Inflows Soar; BlackRock Fund Passes $1 Bln |url=https://www.etf.com/sections/news/spot-bitcoin-etf-inflows-soar-blackrock-fund-passes-1-bln |access-date=28 February 2024 |website=etf.com |archive-date=28 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240228191520/https://www.etf.com/sections/news/spot-bitcoin-etf-inflows-soar-blackrock-fund-passes-1-bln |url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 2023, the company appointed [[Amin H. Nasser]] to its board.<ref>{{Cite news |date=17 July 2023 |title=BlackRock Names Aramco CEO Amin Nasser to Its Board of Directors |language=en |work=Bloomberg.com |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-07-17/blackrock-names-aramco-ceo-amin-nasser-to-its-board-of-directors |access-date=19 July 2023 |archive-date=24 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240224164549/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-07-17/blackrock-names-aramco-ceo-amin-nasser-to-its-board-of-directors |url-status=live }}</ref> Nasser, the Chief Executive Officer of Saudi Aramco, the world's largest oil company, will fill Blackrock's board vacancy left by Bader Alsaad in 2024.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Grover |first=Natalie |date=July 17, 2023 |title=BlackRock names Aramco boss to board |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/blackrock-names-aramco-boss-board-2023-07-17/ |access-date=September 25, 2024 |work=Reuters}}</ref> In August 2023, BlackRock signed an agreement with New Zealand to establish a NZ$2&nbsp;billion investment fund for solar, wind, [[green hydrogen]], battery storage, and [[Charging station|EV charging]] projects as part of its goal of reaching 100% renewable energy by 2030.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hipkins |first1=Chris |last2=Woods |first2=Megan |title=First of its kind climate fund to back 100% renewable energy |url=https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/first-its-kind-climate-fund-back-100-renewable-electricity |website=Beehive.govt.nz |publisher=[[New Zealand Government]] |access-date=14 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231010090823/https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/first-its-kind-climate-fund-back-100-renewable-electricity |archive-date=10 October 2023 |date=8 August 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gibson |first1=Eloise |title=Government partners with US investment giant BlackRock on 2bn fund for solar, wind, hydrogen |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/climate-news/300945414/government-partners-with-us-investment-giant-blackrock-on-2bn-fund-for-solar-wind-hydrogen |access-date=14 October 2023 |work=[[Stuff (company)|Stuff]] |date=9 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230827063836/https://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/climate-news/300945414/government-partners-with-us-investment-giant-blackrock-on-2bn-fund-for-solar-wind-hydrogen |archive-date=27 August 2023|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2024, BlackRock announced that it would acquire the investment fund [[Global Infrastructure Partners]] for $12.5&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 January 2024 |title=BlackRock Agrees to Acquire GIP, Creating a World Leading Infrastructure Private Markets Investment Platform |url=https://www.global-infra.com/news/2024/01/blackrock-agrees-to-acquire-global-infrastructure-partners-gip-creating-a-world-leading-infrastructure-private-markets-investment-platform/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240112135224/https://www.global-infra.com/news/2024/01/blackrock-agrees-to-acquire-global-infrastructure-partners-gip-creating-a-world-leading-infrastructure-private-markets-investment-platform/ |archive-date=2024-01-12 |access-date=2024-01-12 |website=Global Infrastructure Partners |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite news |date=12 January 2024 |title=BlackRock strikes $12.5 bln deal for Global Infrastructure Partners |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/blackrock-quarterly-profit-rises-strong-assets-under-management-2024-01-12/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240112134829/https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/blackrock-quarterly-profit-rises-strong-assets-under-management-2024-01-12/ |archive-date=12 January 2024 |work=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=12 January 2024 |title=BlackRock CEO Larry Fink on GIP deal: The future in private markets will be infrastructure |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cTT_FlYYNtU |access-date=12 January 2024 |website=Youtube – CNBC Television |archive-date=12 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240112135514/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cTT_FlYYNtU |url-status=live }}</ref> BlackRock agreed to pay $3&nbsp;billion in cash and 12 million of its own shares as part of the deal to buy GIP. In March 2024, BlackRock launched their first tokenized fund, the BlackRock USD Institutional Digital Liquidity Fund (BUIDL) on [[Ethereum]], which represents investments in [[United States Treasury security|U.S. Treasury bills]] and repo agreements. The fund secured $245 million in assets in the first week.<ref>{{Cite news |title=BlackRock Launches Its First Tokenized Fund, BUIDL, on the Ethereum Network |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20240320771318/en/BlackRock-Launches-Its-First-Tokenized-Fund-BUIDL-on-the-Ethereum-Network |access-date=2024-05-27 |language=en}}</ref> On July 15, 2024, BlackRock removed from circulation an advertisement filmed in 2022 that briefly featured [[Thomas Matthew Crooks]], the gunman in the [[Attempted assassination of Donald Trump in Pennsylvania|attempted assassination of Donald Trump]].<ref name="q793">{{cite web | last=Victoria Cavaliere | first=Bloomberg | title=Trump shooter was once featured in a BlackRock ad | website=Fortune | date=14 July 2024 | url=https://fortune.com/2024/07/14/thomas-matthew-crooks-donald-trump-assassination-attempt-gunman-blackrock-ad-unpaid/ | access-date=16 July 2024}}</ref><ref name="g499">{{cite web | title=BlackRock says suspect from Trump rally appeared in a 2022 ad | website=Reuters | date=15 July 2024 | url=https://www.reuters.com/world/us/blackrock-says-suspect-trump-rally-appeared-2022-ad-2024-07-15/ | access-date=16 July 2024}}</ref>
The firm expanded its headquarters at 50 Hudson Yards in mid-2024.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wong |first1=Natalie |title=BlackRock Expands New York Offices at Related's 50 Hudson Yards |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-07-31/blackrock-expands-new-york-offices-at-related-s-50-hudson-yards |access-date=31 July 2024 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=31 July 2024 |language=en}}</ref>

==Finances==
In 2020, the non-profit [[American Economic Liberties Project]] issued a report highlighting the fact that "the 'Big Three' asset management firms – BlackRock, [[Vanguard Group|Vanguard]] and [[State Street Corporation|State Street]] – manage over $15 trillion in combined global assets under management, an amount equivalent to more than three-quarters of U.S. gross domestic product."<ref>[https://www.economicliberties.us/our-work/new-money-trust/#_edn13 The New Money Trust: How Large Money Managers Control Our Economy and What We Can Do About It] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220602061203/https://www.economicliberties.us/our-work/new-money-trust/#_edn13 |date=2 June 2022 }}, 23 November 2020</ref> The report called for structural reforms and better regulation of the financial markets. In 2021, BlackRock managed over $10&nbsp;trillion in assets under management, about 40% of the GDP of the United States (nominal $25.347&nbsp;trillion in 2022).<ref name="GDP IMF">{{cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/en/Publications/WEO/weo-database/2022/April|title=World Economic Outlook Database, April 2022|date=April 2022|website=IMF.org|publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]]|access-date=19 April 2022|archive-date=19 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220419134621/https://www.imf.org/en/Publications/WEO/weo-database/2022/April|url-status=live}}</ref>

