==Issues==
===Influence and power===
Due to its power and the sheer size and scope of its financial assets and activities, BlackRock has been called the world's largest [[Shadow banking system|shadow bank]] by ''[[The Economist]]'' and ''[[Basler Zeitung]]''.<ref name=bazonline-br>{{Cite news |title=Die grösste Schattenbank der Welt |work=[[Basler Zeitung]] |url=http://bazonline.ch/wirtschaft/unternehmen-und-konjunktur/Die-groesste-Schattenbank-der-Welt/story/27331110 |date=20 November 2012 |access-date=30 November 2016 |archive-date=10 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211210163309/https://www.bazonline.ch/wirtschaft/unternehmen-und-konjunktur/die-groesste-schattenbank-der-welt/story/27331110 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=econ-br/> In 2020, U.S. Representatives [[Katie Porter]] and [[Jesús "Chuy" García]] proposed a U.S. House bill aiming to restrain BlackRock and other shadow banks.<ref name=vampire/> On March 4, 2021, U.S. Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] suggested that BlackRock should be designated "[[too big to fail]]" and regulated accordingly.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cox |first=Jeff |title=Yellen supports banks' share buybacks. Sen. Warren wants BlackRock designated too big to fail |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/03/24/yellen-supports-buybacks-warren-wants-blackrock-deemed-too-big-to-fail.html |website=[[CNBC]] |date=24 March 2021 |access-date=25 March 2021 |archive-date=1 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501054456/https://www.cnbc.com/2021/03/24/yellen-supports-buybacks-warren-wants-blackrock-deemed-too-big-to-fail.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

BlackRock invests the funds of its clients (for example, the owners of [[iShares]] [[exchange-traded fund]] units) in numerous publicly traded companies, some of which compete with each other.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Fichtner |first1=Jan |last2=Heemskerk |first2=Eelke M. |last3=Garcia-Bernardo |first3=Javier |date=2017 |title=Hidden power of the Big Three? Passive index funds, re-concentration of corporate ownership, and new financial risk |journal=Business and Politics |volume=19 |issue=2 |pages=298–326 |doi=10.1017/bap.2017.6 |doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=3 November 2016 |title=Who owns big business: the rise of passive investors (@uvaCORPNET) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OYpCxXuF3M8 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211221/OYpCxXuF3M8 |archive-date=21 December 2021 |url-status=live|website=YouTube}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=10 May 2018 |title=BlackRock – The company that owns the world? (Investigate Europe) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A4foal20UTA | archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211221/A4foal20UTA |archive-date=21 December 2021 |url-status=live|website=YouTube}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Because of the size of BlackRock's funds, the company is among the top shareholders of many companies. BlackRock states these shares are ultimately owned by the company's clients, not by BlackRock itself—a view shared by multiple independent academics—but acknowledges it can exercise shareholder votes on behalf of these clients, in many cases without client input.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-business-investment-idUSL2N2WI1K4 |title=Fact Check-Video claiming BlackRock and Vanguard 'own all the biggest corporations in the world' is missing context |work=[[Reuters]] |date=20 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230606152755/https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-business-investment-idUSL2N2WI1K4 |archive-date=6 June 2023 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

BlackRock has been the subject of [[conspiracy theories]], including the conspiracy theory that BlackRock owns both [[Fox News]] and [[Dominion Voting Systems]], which [[Snopes]] described as "false" and [[PolitiFact]] described as "mostly false".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/does-blackrock-own-fox-news-dominion-voting/ |title=Does BlackRock Own Both Fox News and Dominion Voting Systems? |date=27 April 2023 |publisher=[[Snopes]] |accessdate=27 April 2023 |archive-date=27 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230427113426/https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/does-blackrock-own-fox-news-dominion-voting/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2023/apr/26/facebook-posts/blackrock-fox-and-tucker-carlson-untangling-a-web/ |title=Facebook posts |accessdate=27 April 2023 |archive-date=27 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230427000329/https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2023/apr/26/facebook-posts/blackrock-fox-and-tucker-carlson-untangling-a-web/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Some BlackRock conspiracy theories have incorporated [[antisemitic conspiracy theories|antisemitism]], such as the conspiracy theory that Jewish people, including BlackRock founder Robert Kapito, are part of a [[cabal]] responsible for [[COVID-19]] and a "[[COVID-19 misinformation|COVID]] agenda".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jpost.com/diaspora/antisemitism/article-712270 |title='COVID agenda is Jewish': Antisemitic flyer found at Melbourne synagogue |date=16 July 2022 |publisher=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |accessdate=27 April 2023 |archive-date=27 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230427113425/https://www.jpost.com/diaspora/antisemitism/article-712270 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Common ownership ===
"Common ownership" is when competitors within a market are commonly owned. In other words, these competitors can have the same powerful shareholders if their shares trade publicly. Common ownership has the potential to cause harm because it reduces market competition, which can be bad for consumers and the economy. In response to a widely cited research paper that showed that common ownership raises prices,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Why the presence of common shareholders in rival companies looms as a threat |url=https://www.iese.edu/insight/articles/common-shareholders-rival-companies-threat/ |access-date=2024-06-06 |website=IESE Insight |language=en-US}}</ref> BlackRock issued a white paper calling the mechanism "vague and implausible". At the same time, the research’s findings was listed as a "risk" in BlackRock's annual report. Common ownership can also lead to higher pay for CEOs, even as competition between the firms is reduced.<ref>{{Cite web |title=When sky-high executive pay is a case of common ownership |url=https://www.iese.edu/insight/articles/sky-high-executive-pay-common-ownership/ |access-date=2024-06-06 |website=IESE Insight |language=en-US}}</ref>
===Environmental, social and corporate governance investing===
{{main|Environmental, social and corporate governance}}

In 2017, BlackRock expanded its [[environmental, social and corporate governance]] (ESG) projects with new staff and products.<ref>{{Cite news |date=22 October 2018 |title=BlackRock stakes claim on 'sustainable investing' revolution |work=[[Financial Times]] |url=https://www.ft.com/content/f66b2a9e-d53d-11e8-a854-33d6f82e62f8 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103131328/https://www.ft.com/content/f66b2a9e-d53d-11e8-a854-33d6f82e62f8 |archive-date=3 November 2018 |url-status=bot: unknown |quote=BlackRock intends to become a global leader in “sustainable investing”, says Larry Fink, as the world's largest asset manager launched |url-access=subscription |access-date=3 November 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Chasan |first=Emily |date=10 October 2017 |title=BlackRock Names Former Obama Aide to Run Sustainable Investing |work=Bloomberg |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-10/blackrock-names-former-obama-aide-to-run-sustainable-investing |access-date=3 November 2018 |archive-date=6 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220506020948/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-10/blackrock-names-former-obama-aide-to-run-sustainable-investing |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Jarsh |first1=Melissa |last2=Chasan |first2=Emily |date=13 June 2018 |title=BlackRock, Wells Fargo Are Betting on Ethical Investing Funds for 401(k)s |work=Bloomberg |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-13/blackrock-wells-fargo-are-said-to-push-esg-funds-for-401-k-s |access-date=3 November 2018 |archive-date=27 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227212546/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-13/blackrock-wells-fargo-are-said-to-push-esg-funds-for-401-k-s |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Camilla Giannoni |date=19 October 2018 |title=BlackRock hires new Switzerland CEO |url=https://citywire.ch/news/blackrock-hires-new-switzerland-ceo/a1167087 |quote=deepen our commitment to clients in Switzerland and broaden our sustainable investing footprint in Europe |access-date=3 November 2018 |archive-date=29 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210129230207/https://citywire.ch/news/blackrock-hires-new-switzerland-ceo/a1167087 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title=Independent Capital's Staub-Bisang to run BlackRock Switzerland | first=Angelika | last=Gruber | work=[[Reuters]] | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/blackrock-swiss/moves-independent-capitals-staub-bisang-to-run-blackrock-switzerland-idUSL8N1WZ49G | date=19 October 2018 | access-date=3 November 2018 | archive-date=31 October 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201031182352/https://www.reuters.com/article/blackrock-swiss/moves-independent-capitals-staub-bisang-to-run-blackrock-switzerland-idUSL8N1WZ49G | url-status=live }}</ref>{{overcite|date=March 2024}} BlackRock started drawing attention to environmental and diversity issues by means of official letters to CEOs and shareholder votes together with [[activist investor]]s or investor networks such as the [[Carbon Disclosure Project]], which in 2017 backed a shareholder resolution for [[ExxonMobil]] to act on [[climate change]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tarek Soliman |title=The new normal: Exxon shareholders vote in favour of climate action |url=https://www.cdp.net/en/articles/investor/the-new-normal-exxon-shareholders-vote-in-favour-of-climate-action |date=1 June 2017 |access-date=3 November 2018 |archive-date=29 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210129230157/https://www.cdp.net/en/articles/investor/the-new-normal-exxon-shareholders-vote-in-favour-of-climate-action |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Gary McWilliams |date=31 May 2017 |title=Exxon shareholders approve climate impact report in win for activists |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-exxonmobil-climate-idUSKBN18R0DC |access-date=3 November 2018 |archive-date=7 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210507064600/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-exxonmobil-climate-idUSKBN18R0DC |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |first=Andrew |last=Winston |title=Does Wall Street Finally Care About Sustainability? |url=https://hbr.org/2018/01/does-wall-street-finally-care-about-sustainability |journal=[[Harvard Business Review]] |date=19 January 2018 |access-date=3 November 2018 |archive-date=1 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501054456/https://hbr.org/2018/01/does-wall-street-finally-care-about-sustainability |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, it asked [[Russell 1000]] companies to improve [[gender diversity]] on their board of directors if they had fewer than two women on them.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Chasan |first=Emily |date=3 November 2018 |title=BlackRock Is Sick of Excuses for Corporate Boards Lacking Women |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-11-03/blackrock-is-sick-of-excuses-for-corporate-boards-lacking-women |website=Bloomberg |access-date=3 November 2018 }}</ref>

In August 2021, a former BlackRock executive who had served as the company's first global chief investment officer for sustainable investing, said he thought the firm's ESG investing was a "dangerous placebo that harms the public interest." The former executive said that financial institutions are motivated to engage in ESG investing because ESG products have higher fees, which in turn increase company profits.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Amaro |first1=Silvia |title=Blackrock's former sustainable investing chief now thinks ESG is a 'dangerous placebo' |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/08/24/blackrocks-former-sustainable-investing-chief-says-esg-is-a-dangerous-placebo.html |access-date=26 October 2021 |work=CNBC |date=24 August 2021 |language=en |archive-date=3 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220603155515/https://www.cnbc.com/2021/08/24/blackrocks-former-sustainable-investing-chief-says-esg-is-a-dangerous-placebo.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2021, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' editorial board wrote that BlackRock was pushing the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] to adopt rules requiring private companies to publicly disclose their climate impact, the diversity of their boards of directors, and other metrics. The editorial board opined that "ESG mandates, which also carry substantial litigation and reputation risks, will cause many companies to shun public markets. This would hurt stock exchanges and asset managers, but most of all retail investors."<ref>{{cite news |title=Opinion: BlackRock's Wish Is Your Command |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/follow-larry-finks-orders-or-else-blackrock-nasdaq-adena-friedman-esg-sec-11633112228 |author=The Editorial Board |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=24 October 2021 |url-access=subscription |access-date=26 October 2021 |archive-date=2 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220202193935/https://www.wsj.com/articles/follow-larry-finks-orders-or-else-blackrock-nasdaq-adena-friedman-esg-sec-11633112228 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In January 2022, BlackRock founder and CEO Larry Fink defended the company's focus on ESG investing, pushing back "against accusations the asset manager was using its heft and influence to support a [[politically correct]] or [[progressivism|progressive]] agenda."<ref name="cnbc">{{cite news |last1=Meredith |first1=Sam |title=BlackRock CEO Larry Fink says stakeholder capitalism is not 'woke' |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/01/18/blackrock-ceo-larry-fink-says-stakeholder-capitalism-is-not-woke.html |work=CNBC |date=18 January 2022 |access-date=18 January 2022 |archive-date=11 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220511121237/https://www.cnbc.com/2022/01/18/blackrock-ceo-larry-fink-says-stakeholder-capitalism-is-not-woke.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Fink said the practice of ESG "is not [[woke]]".<ref>{{cite news |title=BlackRock CEO Says Stakeholder Capitalism Isn't 'Woke' |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-01-18/blackrock-ceo-says-nothing-woke-about-stakeholder-capitalism |last1=Brush |first1=Silla |last2=Ward |first2=Russell |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=17 January 2022 |url-access=limited |access-date=18 January 2022 |archive-date=18 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220118132510/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-01-18/blackrock-ceo-says-nothing-woke-about-stakeholder-capitalism |url-status=live }}</ref> BlackRock's emphasis on ESG has drawn criticism as "either bowing to anti-business interests" or being "merely marketing".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/01/18/business/dealbook/fink-blackrock-woke.html |last1=Sorkin |first1=Andrew Ross |authorlink1=Andrew Ross Sorkin |last2=Karaian |first2=Jason |last3=Kessler |first3=Sarah |last4=Gandel |first4=Stephen |last5=Merced |first5=Michael J. de la |last6=Hirsch |first6=Lauren |last7=Livni |first7=Ephrat |title=Larry Fink Defends Stakeholder Capitalism |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=18 January 2022 |access-date=18 January 2022 |archive-date=6 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220606155955/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/01/18/business/dealbook/fink-blackrock-woke.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In a talk at the [[Aspen Ideas Festival]] in June 2023, BlackRock CEO Larry Fink said he has stopped using the term "ESG" because the term has been "weaponized". According to an ''[[Axios (website)|Axios]]'' reporter, Fink said, "I'm ashamed of being part of this conversation." Later, according to ''Axios'', Fink said, "I never said I was ashamed. I'm not ashamed. I do believe in conscientious capitalism."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.axios.com/2023/06/26/larry-fink-ashamed-esg-weaponized-desantis |last1=Frank |first1=John |title=Larry Fink "ashamed" to be part of ESG political debate |work=[[Axios (website)|Axios]] |date=26 June 2023 |access-date=26 June 2023 |archive-date=26 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230626183241/https://www.axios.com/2023/06/26/larry-fink-ashamed-esg-weaponized-desantis |url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 2023, BlackRock announced that it would allow retail investors a [[proxy vote]] in its biggest ETF from 2024. The move was initiated in the context of claims from US Republicans that Blackrock is systematically trying to push a 'woke agenda' through its pro-ESG activities. Under the plan, investors in BlackRock's iShares Core S&P 500 ETF will be asked to make choices from seven different general policies ranging from voting generally with BlackRock's management, to environmental, social and governance factors or prioritizing Catholic values. Investors will not be able to vote on specific companies.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Masters |first=Brooke |date=17 July 2023 |title=BlackRock offers a vote to retail investors in its biggest ETF |work=Financial Times |url=https://www.ft.com/content/3f0f26bf-cb33-4fd4-a1dd-4104cd294b17 |access-date=17 July 2023 |url-access=subscription |archive-date=17 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230717152547/https://www.ft.com/content/3f0f26bf-cb33-4fd4-a1dd-4104cd294b17 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Editorial Board at The Wall Street Journal|Editorial Board at ''The Wall Street Journal'']] argued that it amounted to a "false voting choice" since almost all of the pre-selected voting policies are devised by the ESG-aligned proxy advisories [[Glass Lewis]] and [[Institutional Shareholder Services]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/blackrocks-false-voting-choice-proxy-esg-ballots-iss-glass-lewis-66652357 |title=BlackRock's False Voting 'Choice' |date=24 July 2023 |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=25 July 2023 |archive-date=25 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230725054150/https://www.wsj.com/articles/blackrocks-false-voting-choice-proxy-esg-ballots-iss-glass-lewis-66652357 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Investments in contributors to climate change===
[[File:XR_and_GreenFaith_activists_protest_BlackRock,_May_31_2022.jpg|thumb|Environmental activists, including global interfaith organization [[GreenFaith]] and [[Extinction Rebellion]], protest BlackRock's shareholder meeting on May 31, 2022. ]]
GreenFaith activists protested BlackRock's shareholder meeting on May 31, 2022. Activists including director Fletcher Harper were arrested. As of December 2018, BlackRock was the world's largest investor in [[coal-fired power station]]s, holding shares worth $11&nbsp;billion in 56 companies in the industry.<ref>{{Cite web |title=New Research Reveals the Banks and Investors Financing the Expansion of the Global Coal Plant Fleet |url=https://urgewald.org/medien/new-research-reveals-banks-and-investors-financing-expansion-global-coal-plant-fleet |work=[[Urgewald]] |date=5 December 2018 |access-date=14 December 2018 |archive-date=23 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220423193825/https://www.urgewald.org/medien/new-research-reveals-banks-and-investors-financing-expansion-global-coal-plant-fleet |url-status=live }}</ref> BlackRock owned more oil, gas, and thermal coal reserves than any other investment management company with total reserves amounting to 9.5 gigatonnes of {{CO2}} emissions or 30% of total energy-related emissions from 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |title=New report confirms BlackRock's big fossil fuel problem |url=https://foe.org/news/new-report-confirms-blackrocks-big-fossil-fuel-problem/ |work=[[Friends of the Earth]] |date=10 December 2018 |access-date=14 December 2018 |archive-date=9 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220409054038/https://foe.org/news/new-report-confirms-blackrocks-big-fossil-fuel-problem/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Environmental groups including the [[Sierra Club]],<ref>{{Cite news |title=New Campaign Is Calling Out BlackRock's Big Climate Problem |url=https://www.sierraclub.org/compass/2018/10/new-campaign-calling-out-blackrock-s-big-climate-problem |website=[[Sierra Club]] |date=5 October 2018 |access-date=24 January 2019 |archive-date=1 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501160704/https://www.sierraclub.org/compass/2018/10/new-campaign-calling-out-blackrock-s-big-climate-problem |url-status=live }}</ref> as well as [[Amazon Watch]],<ref>{{Cite web |title=BlackRock Targeted as Largest Driver of Climate Destruction in New Campaign |url=https://amazonwatch.org/news/2018/0926-blackrock-targeted-as-largest-driver-of-climate-destruction-in-new-campaign |website=[[Amazon Watch]] |date=27 September 2018 |access-date=24 January 2019 |archive-date=9 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220409054038/https://amazonwatch.org/news/2018/0926-blackrock-targeted-as-largest-driver-of-climate-destruction-in-new-campaign |url-status=live }}</ref> launched a campaign in September 2018 called "BlackRock's Big Problem",<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |title=BlackRock's Big Problem- Making the climate crisis worse |url=https://www.blackrocksbigproblem.com/ |website=BlackRock's Big Problem |access-date=24 January 2019 |archive-date=5 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220605065933/https://blackrocksbigproblem.com/ |url-status=live }}</ref> claiming that BlackRock is the "biggest driver of climate destruction on the planet", in part due to its opposition to [[fossil fuel divestment]].<ref name=":3" />

In 2019, climate activists carried out street theatre and glued themselves to the door of the company's London offices.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Hammond |first1=Holly |last2=McIntyre |first2=Iain |date=9 March 2022 |title="You can't eat money": An interview with Extinction Rebellion activist Jo Flanagan |url=https://commonslibrary.org/you-cant-eat-money/ |access-date=23 October 2023 |website=The Commons Social Change Library |language=en-AU |archive-date=2 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231002120324/https://commonslibrary.org/you-cant-eat-money/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On January 10, 2020, a group of climate activists rushed inside the Paris offices of BlackRock France, painting walls and floors with warnings and accusations on the responsibility of the company in the [[effects of global warming]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=BlackRock's Paris Office Barricaded by Climate Activists |website=[[Bloomberg News]] |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-10/blackrock-s-paris-office-barricaded-by-climate-activists |first=Gaspard |last=Sebag |date=10 February 2020 |url-access=limited |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-date=26 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201126223052/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-10/blackrock-s-paris-office-barricaded-by-climate-activists |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2019, BlackRock was criticized for the environmental impact of its holdings as it was a major shareholder in every oil [[supermajors|supermajor]] except [[Total S.A.]] and in 7 of the 10 biggest coal producers.<ref>{{Cite news |title=World's biggest investor accused of dragging feet on climate crisis |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/may/21/blackrock-investor-climate-crisis-blackrock-assets |date=21 May 2019 |access-date=21 May 2019 |archive-date=5 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220205191100/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/may/21/blackrock-investor-climate-crisis-blackrock-assets |url-status=live }}</ref>

On January 14, 2020, the company shifted its investment policy; BlackRock CEO [[Larry Fink]] said that environmental [[sustainability]] would be a key goal for investment decisions.<ref name=":5">{{Cite news |last=Sorkin |first=Andrew Ross |authorlink=Andrew Ross Sorkin |title=BlackRock C.E.O. Larry Fink: Climate Crisis Will Reshape Finance |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/14/business/dealbook/larry-fink-blackrock-climate-change.html |date=14 January 2020 |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=16 January 2020 |archive-date=25 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220525020110/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/14/business/dealbook/larry-fink-blackrock-climate-change.html |url-status=live }}</ref> BlackRock announced that it would sell $500&nbsp;million worth of coal-related assets, and created funds that would not invest in companies profiting from [[fossil fuels]].<ref name=":6">{{Cite web | title=BlackRock to sell $500 million in coal investments in climate change push | url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/blackrock-puts-climate-change-first-in-its-its-investment-strategy/ | first=STEPHEN | last=GANDEL | website=[[CBS News]] | date=14 January 2020 | access-date=16 January 2020 | archive-date=6 May 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220506131141/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/blackrock-puts-climate-change-first-in-its-its-investment-strategy/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":5" /> Nonetheless, BlackRock's support for shareholder resolutions requesting [[climate risk]] disclosure fell from 25% in 2019 to 14% in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cook |first=Jackie |title=How Big Fund Families Voted on Climate Change: 2020 Edition |url=https://www.morningstar.com/articles/1002749/how-big-fund-families-voted-on-climate-change-2020-edition |work=[[Morningstar, Inc.]] |date=28 September 2020 |access-date=20 October 2020 |archive-date=9 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220409150858/https://www.morningstar.com/articles/1002749/how-big-fund-families-voted-on-climate-change-2020-edition |url-status=live }}</ref> BlackRock has also been criticized regarding [[climate change]] inaction and [[deforestation]] in the [[Amazon rainforest]].<ref>{{Cite news | first=Stephen | last=Gandel | url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/amazon-fires-blackrock-investment-firm-financial-role-cbsn-originals-documentary/ | title=Investment giant BlackRock faces critics on climate change, Amazon deforestation | work=[[CBS News]] | date=2 March 2020 | access-date=30 December 2020 | archive-date=31 December 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201231075301/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/amazon-fires-blackrock-investment-firm-financial-role-cbsn-originals-documentary/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | first=Patrick | last=Greenfield | url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/oct/12/top-three-asset-managers-fossil-fuel-investments | title=World's Top Three Asset Managers Oversee $300bn Fossil Fuel Investments | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=12 October 2019 | access-date=30 December 2020 | archive-date=31 December 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201231075420/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/oct/12/top-three-asset-managers-fossil-fuel-investments | url-status=live }}</ref> According to ''[[The New Republic]]'', BlackRock "has positioned itself as the good guy on [[Wall Street]], and its executives as a crew of mild-mannered money managers who understand the risks of the climate crisis and the importance of diversity. But those commitments, critics say, only extend so far into the firm's day-to-day operations."<ref name="vampire">{{cite magazine |last=Aronoff |first=Kate |title=Is BlackRock the New Vampire Squid? |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/158263/blackrock-climate-change-fossil-fuel-investments |magazine=[[The New Republic]] |date=26 June 2020 |access-date=30 December 2020 |archive-date=27 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220527114526/https://newrepublic.com/article/158263/blackrock-climate-change-fossil-fuel-investments |url-status=live }}</ref> According to [[IESE Business School|IESE]], BlackRock has indeed influenced polluting companies to lower their carbon emissions. The study showed that companies who met with BlackRock’s CEO Larry Fink had lower CO2 emissions the following year.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The sweeping change of net zero emissions |url=https://www.iese.edu/insight/articles/change-zero-emissions/ |access-date=2024-06-06 |website=IESE Insight |language=en-US}}</ref>

===Investments in gun manufacturers ===
In May 2018, anti-gun protesters held a demonstration outside the company's [[annual general meeting]] in Manhattan.<ref>{{Cite news | first1=Chelsia Rose | last1=Marcius | first2=Rich | last2=Schapiro | title=Anti-gun protesters rally outside BlackRock shareholder meeting to condemn its Sturm Ruger investments | url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/anti-gun-protesters-rally-blackrock-shareholder-meeting-article-1.4005409 | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=23 May 2018 | access-date=3 November 2019 | archive-date=1 May 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501163758/https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/anti-gun-protesters-rally-blackrock-shareholder-meeting-article-1.4005409 | url-status=live }}</ref> After discussions with firearms manufacturers and distributors, on April 5, 2018, BlackRock introduced two new [[exchange-traded fund]]s (ETFs) that exclude stocks of gun makers and large gun retailers such as [[Walmart]], [[Dick's Sporting Goods]], [[Kroger]], [[Sturm Ruger]], [[American Outdoor Brands]], and [[Vista Outdoor]], and removed the stocks from seven existing ESG funds.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Moyer |first=Liz |title=BlackRock to offer new funds that exclude stocks of gun makers and retailers including Walmart |work=[[CNBC]] |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/05/blackrock-to-offer-new-funds-that-exclude-stocks-of-gun-makers-and-retailers-including-walmart.html |date=5 April 2018 |access-date=3 April 2019 |archive-date=10 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210210025800/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/05/blackrock-to-offer-new-funds-that-exclude-stocks-of-gun-makers-and-retailers-including-walmart.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Gibson |first=Kate |title=BlackRock unveils line of gun-free investment products |work=[[CBS News]] |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/blackrock-unveils-line-of-gun-free-investment-products/ |date=5 April 2018 |access-date=3 April 2019 |archive-date=29 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210129230155/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/blackrock-unveils-line-of-gun-free-investment-products/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Siegel |first=Rachel |title=BlackRock unveils gun-free investment options |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2018/04/06/blackrock-unveils-gun-free-investment-options/ |date=6 April 2018 |access-date=3 April 2019 |archive-date=3 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403124747/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2018/04/06/blackrock-unveils-gun-free-investment-options/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

===BlackRock study on integrating ESG into banking rules===
The [[European Ombudsman]] opened an inquiry in May 2020 to inspect the commission's file on the [[European Commission]]'s decision to award a contract to BlackRock to carry out a study on integrating environmental, social and governance risks and objectives into EU banking rules ('the prudential framework'). [[European Parliament]] members questioned the impartiality of BlackRock given its investments in the sector.<ref>{{Cite web | title=European Ombudsman | url=https://www.ombudsman.europa.eu/fr/case/en/57060 | work=[[Europa (web portal)|Europa]] | date=23 November 2020 | access-date=23 September 2020 | archive-date=30 November 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201130153636/https://www.ombudsman.europa.eu/fr/case/en/57060 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=The Commission's decision to award a contract to BlackRock to oversee the development of ESG factors in the EU banking sector and corporate investment policies |url=https://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/P-9-2020-002369_EN.html |work=[[Europa (web portal)|Europa]] |date=20 April 2020 |access-date=23 September 2020 |archive-date=1 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501165035/https://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/P-9-2020-002369_EN.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

===U.S. states refusing to do business with BlackRock due to ESG policies===
[[Riley Moore]], the [[state treasurer]] of West Virginia, said in June 2022 that BlackRock and five other financial institutions would no longer be allowed to do business with the state of West Virginia because of the company's advocacy against the fossil fuel industry.<ref>{{cite news |title=West Virginia threatens to bar big banks, BlackRock over perceived fossil fuel boycotts |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/west-virginia-threatens-bar-big-banks-blackrock-over-perceived-fossil-fuel-2022-06-14/ |last=Schroeder |first=Pete |work=[[Reuters]] |date=14 June 2022 |access-date=17 June 2022 |archive-date=17 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220617180616/https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/west-virginia-threatens-bar-big-banks-blackrock-over-perceived-fossil-fuel-2022-06-14/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2022, Louisiana removed $794&nbsp;million from BlackRock due to the company's support of ESG and green energy.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/business/sustainable-business/louisiana-remove-794-mln-blackrock-funds-over-esg-drive-2022-10-05/ | title=Louisiana to remove $794 mln from BlackRock funds over ESG drive | first1=Niket | last1=Nishant | first2=Mehr | last2=Bedi | work=[[Reuters]] | date=5 October 2022 | access-date=7 April 2023 | archive-date=30 March 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230330210530/https://www.reuters.com/business/sustainable-business/louisiana-remove-794-mln-blackrock-funds-over-esg-drive-2022-10-05/ | url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2022, [[Jimmy Patronis]], the chief financial officer of Florida, announced that the [[government of Florida]] would be divesting $2&nbsp;billion worth of investments under management by BlackRock due to the firm's move to strengthen ESG standards and ESG policies.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Florida pulls $2B worth of investments from BlackRock over ESG investment after DeSantis resolution |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/3759466-florida-pulls-2b-worth-of-investments-from-blackrock-over-esg-investment-after-desantis-resolution/ |last=Folmar |first=Chloe |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=2 December 2022 |access-date=4 December 2022 |archive-date=4 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221204213311/https://thehill.com/homenews/3759466-florida-pulls-2b-worth-of-investments-from-blackrock-over-esg-investment-after-desantis-resolution/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Florida to pull $2bn from BlackRock in spreading ESG backlash |work=[[Financial Times]] |url=https://www.ft.com/content/38f87ec9-41c6-441d-a6c2-314ff0435166 |date=1 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221204213713/https://www.ft.com/content/38f87ec9-41c6-441d-a6c2-314ff0435166 |archive-date=4 December 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=bot: unknown |access-date=4 December 2022 }}</ref> BlackRock later responded to the announcement with a statement stating that the divestment would place politics over investor interest.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/florida-pulls-2-bln-blackrock-largest-anti-esg-divestment-2022-12-01/ | title=Florida pulls $2 bln from BlackRock in largest anti-ESG divestment | work=[[Reuters]] | last=Kerber | first=Ross | date=1 December 2022 | access-date=4 December 2022 | archive-date=4 December 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221204213316/https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/florida-pulls-2-bln-blackrock-largest-anti-esg-divestment-2022-12-01/ | url-status=live }}</ref>

===Criticism of investments in China===
In August 2021, BlackRock set up its first mutual fund in China after raising over one billion dollars from 111,000 Chinese investors. BlackRock became the first foreign-owned company allowed by the Chinese government to operate a wholly-owned business in China's mutual fund industry.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chandler |first1=Clay |last2=Gordon |first2=Nicholas |title=BlackRock is 'blundering' in China—all the way to the bank |url=https://fortune.com/2021/09/09/blackrock-china-mutual-fund-investment-soros-mistake/ |access-date=25 October 2021 |work=Fortune |date=9 September 2021 |language=en |archive-date=9 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220109100019/https://fortune.com/2021/09/09/blackrock-china-mutual-fund-investment-soros-mistake/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Madhok |first1=Diksha |title=Chinese investors pour $1 billion into BlackRock's new fund |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/09/08/investing/blackrock-china-fund-intl-hnk/index.html |access-date=25 October 2021 |work=CNN |date=8 September 2021 |archive-date=13 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220213205242/https://edition.cnn.com/2021/09/08/investing/blackrock-china-fund-intl-hnk/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=BlackRock's China unit raises $1 bln in maiden mutual fund |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/blackrocks-china-unit-raises-1-bln-maiden-mutual-fund-2021-09-08/ |work=Reuters |date=8 September 2021 |language=en |access-date=25 October 2021 |archive-date=20 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120071106/https://www.reuters.com/business/blackrocks-china-unit-raises-1-bln-maiden-mutual-fund-2021-09-08/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Writing in ''The Wall Street Journal'', [[George Soros]] described BlackRock's initiative in China as a "tragic mistake" that would "damage the national security interests of the U.S. and other democracies."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Meredith |first1=Sam |title=BlackRock responds to George Soros' criticism over China investments |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/09/08/blackrock-responds-to-george-soros-criticism-over-china-investments.html |access-date=25 October 2021 |work=CNBC |date=8 September 2021 |language=en |archive-date=11 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220411205223/https://www.cnbc.com/2021/09/08/blackrock-responds-to-george-soros-criticism-over-china-investments.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Soros |first=George |title=Opinion: BlackRock's China Blunder |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/blackrock-larry-fink-china-hkex-sse-authoritarianism-xi-jinping-term-limits-human-rights-ant-didi-global-national-security-11630938728 |date=6 September 2021 |issn=0099-9660 |access-date=24 March 2022 |archive-date=9 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220609074502/https://www.wsj.com/articles/blackrock-larry-fink-china-hkex-sse-authoritarianism-xi-jinping-term-limits-human-rights-ant-didi-global-national-security-11630938728 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Meredith |first=Sam |title=BlackRock responds to George Soros' criticism over China investments |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/09/08/blackrock-responds-to-george-soros-criticism-over-china-investments.html |website=[[CNBC]] |date=8 September 2021 |access-date=25 October 2021 |archive-date=11 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220411205223/https://www.cnbc.com/2021/09/08/blackrock-responds-to-george-soros-criticism-over-china-investments.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In October 2021, non-profit group [[Consumers' Research]] launched an ad campaign criticizing BlackRock's relationship with the Chinese government.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rapoza|first=Kenneth|date=27 October 2021|title=BlackRock's China Relationship Target In Nationwide Ad Campaign|work=[[Forbes]]|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2021/10/27/blackrocks-china-relationship-target-in-nationwide-ad-campaign/|access-date=27 October 2021|archive-date=5 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220505202251/https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2021/10/27/blackrocks-china-relationship-target-in-nationwide-ad-campaign/|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2021, it was reported that BlackRock was an investor in two companies that had been blacklisted by the US government accusing China of [[Uyghurs#Human rights abuses against Uyghurs in Xinjiang|human rights abuses]] against the [[Uyghurs]] in Xinjiang. In one case ([[Hikvision]]) BlackRock increased its level of investment after the company's blacklisting.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fa-mag.com/news/nonprofit-warns-governors-about-blackrock-retirement-funds--chinese-investments-65225.html |title=Nonprofit Warns Governors About BlackRock Retirement Funds' Chinese Investments |website=fa-mag.com |date=3 December 2021 |access-date=12 December 2021 |archive-date=1 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501054459/https://www.fa-mag.com/news/nonprofit-warns-governors-about-blackrock-retirement-funds--chinese-investments-65225.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2023, the [[United States House Select Committee on Strategic Competition between the United States and the Chinese Communist Party|US House of Representatives' Select Committee on the Chinese Communist Party]] initiated an investigation into the firm's investments in Chinese companies accused of violating human rights and aiding the [[People's Liberation Army]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Suter |first=Tara |date=1 August 2023 |title=House China committee launches probe into investment firm BlackRock |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/4131522-house-china-committee-probe-blackrock/ |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=2 August 2023 |archive-date=2 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230802042823/https://thehill.com/homenews/house/4131522-house-china-committee-probe-blackrock/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=O’Keeffe |first1=Kate |last2=Driebusch |first2=Corrie |date=1 August 2023 |title=BlackRock, MSCI Face Congressional Probes for Facilitating China Investments |language=en-US |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/blackrock-msci-face-congressional-probes-for-facilitating-china-investments-2147ce2c |url-access=subscription |access-date=2 August 2023 |issn=0099-9660 |archive-date=1 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230801230329/https://www.wsj.com/articles/blackrock-msci-face-congressional-probes-for-facilitating-china-investments-2147ce2c |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Quinn |first=Jimmy |date=3 August 2023 |title=House Committee: BlackRock Has Funneled over $429 Million to Blacklisted Chinese Firms |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2023/08/house-committee-blackrock-has-funneled-over-429-million-to-blacklisted-chinese-firms/ |access-date=5 September 2023 |website=[[National Review]] |language=en-US |archive-date=5 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230905035246/https://www.nationalreview.com/2023/08/house-committee-blackrock-has-funneled-over-429-million-to-blacklisted-chinese-firms/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The committee concluded that BlackRock channeled $1.9 billion into blacklisted entities in 2023.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Biswas |first1=Pritam |last2=Yasmin |first2=Mehnaz |date=April 18, 2024 |title=US firms channeled funds to blacklisted Chinese companies, says House panel |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/wall-street-steered-billions-blacklisted-chinese-companies-probe-wsj-reports-2024-04-18/ |access-date=April 18, 2024 |work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>

===Ties with Federal Reserve===
BlackRock was scrutinized for allegedly taking advantage of its close ties with the [[Federal Reserve]] during the COVID-19 pandemic response efforts.<ref>Leslie P. Norton. [https://www.barrons.com/articles/blackrock-is-biggest-beneficiary-of-fed-purchases-of-corporate-bond-etfs-51591034726 BlackRock Is Biggest Beneficiary of Fed Purchases of Corporate Bond ETFs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210116100638/https://www.barrons.com/articles/blackrock-is-biggest-beneficiary-of-fed-purchases-of-corporate-bond-etfs-51591034726 |date=16 January 2021 }}, ''Barron's'', 1 June 2020</ref><ref>Richard Henderson and Robin Wigglesworth. [https://www.ft.com/content/08b897a5-aadb-40d7-922c-431154ed968a Fed's big boost for BlackRock raises eyebrows on Wall Street] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201224153727/https://www.ft.com/content/08b897a5-aadb-40d7-922c-431154ed968a |date=24 December 2020 }}, ''Financial Times'', 27 March 2020</ref><ref>Richard Henderson and Robin Wigglesworth. [https://www.ft.com/content/6a587ebf-064d-48a2-9817-9bc6ccc80591 BlackRock's growing clout carries risks for asset manager: Group faces increased scrutiny as central banks ask it to help run stimulus packages] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210104114155/https://www.ft.com/content/6a587ebf-064d-48a2-9817-9bc6ccc80591 |date=4 January 2021 }}, ''Financial Times'', 30 April 2020</ref> In June 2020, ''[[The New Republic]]'' wrote that BlackRock "was having a very good pandemic" and was casting "itself as socially responsible while contributing to the climate catastrophe, evading regulatory scrutiny, and angling to influence [a potential] [[Presidency of Joe Biden|Biden administration]]."<ref name=vampire/> The ''[[Financial Times]]'' described BlackRock as having secured a prominent advisory role in the Fed's post-COVID [[Quantitative easing|asset purchase program]], prompting concerns over whether BlackRock would use its influence to encourage the Fed to purchase BlackRock products; during the Fed's 2020 quantitative easing program, BlackRock's corporate bond ETF received $4.3&nbsp;billion in new investment, compared to the respective $33&nbsp;million and $15&nbsp;million received by BlackRock's competitors [[The Vanguard Group|Vanguard Group]] and [[State Street Corporation|State Street]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=20 May 2020 |title=BlackRock trounces ETF rivals after Fed appointment |work=Financial Times |url=https://www.ft.com/content/7091a2a5-7eef-4c78-8331-9fd986925f8a |access-date=18 February 2023 |archive-date=18 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230218222910/https://www.ft.com/content/7091a2a5-7eef-4c78-8331-9fd986925f8a |url-status=live }}</ref> On May 26, 2020, the contract was released publicly. ''The New York Times'' wrote about the contract that BlackRock "will earn no more than $7.75 million per year for the main bond portfolio it will manage. It will also be prohibited from earning fees on the sale of bond-backed exchange traded funds, a segment of the market it dominates."<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/business/coronavirus-blackrock-federal-reserve.html New York Times 3/27/2020]</ref>

=== Investments in cryptocurrency ===
As of 2024, BlackRock operates the world's largest bitcoin fund.<ref>{{Cite web |last=McGee |first=Suzanne |date=29 May 2024 |title=BlackRock's ETF becomes largest bitcoin fund in world, Bloomberg News reports |url=https://www.reuters.com/technology/blackrocks-etf-becomes-largest-bitcoin-fund-world-bloomberg-news-reports-2024-05-29/#:~:text=May%2029%20(Reuters)%20%2D%20BlackRock's,Bloomberg%20News%20reported%20on%20Wednesday. |access-date=28 June 2024 |website=Reuters}}</ref>

===AI Investment===
Pyramid Analytics, an [[Artificial intelligence|AI]] and analytics company, has secured a strategic $50 million investment from BlackRock, strengthening its position in the enterprise AI and data analytics market to support further technological development and global expansion.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/technology/ai-analytics-firm-pyramid-analytics-secures-50-mln-blackrock-2024-11-25/</ref>

